column47: The Provision of a Core+ 2 Service on behalf of NHS Heywood, Middleton and Rochdale Clinical Commissioning Group
column48:
NHS SBS are acting on behalf of NHS Heywood, Middleton and Rochdale Clinical Commissioning Group ('the Contracting Authority')) to obtain a Provider to deliver a clinically safe and competent Core+ 2 Service which is designed to improve outcomes and reduce variation across the whole of the Rochdale Borough covering a population base of approximately 230,000 patients. The Provision of the Core+ 2 Service consists of seven themes, with each theme containing sub indicators, of which can be viewed within the Service Specification located on the EU-Supply Portal. The Contracting Authority seeks responses from interested Providers who wish to deliver the Service as set out in the Service Specification. Interested Providers must complete and submit a Qualification Questionnaire (QQ). Providers are asked to indicate their proposed bidding model within their QQ response. Where Bidder Members are involved in the proposed model they should also complete the required sections of the QQ. Full details of this can be found in the Bidder Instruction Document. All documents are available electronically via EU Supply - https://nhssbs.eu-supply.com. Please see the QQ Bidder Instruction Document for an overview of the procurement process. The QQ includes Grounds for Exclusion, Economic and Financial Standing and Technical and Professional Ability including:
- Contract Specific Technical Questions: A series of scored questions under the criteria of: (1) Deliverability; (2) Quality; (3) Integration and Transformation; and (4) Organisational Sustainability. Some questions ask Bidders to refer to previous experience. Other questions ask Bidders to explain their understanding of local requirements for the Core+2 Service and in some instances their proposed approach to delivery of the Service. This flexibility of approach is utilised as permitted under the 'light touch regime'.
- Standard Technical Questions: A series of Pass/Fail questions dealing with aspects relevant to service provision, for example, CQC Registration, Insurances, Regulatory etc. This will be a Qualification Stage followed by an Award Stage. The Award Stage will involve invitation of proposals which will be evaluated against award criteria and is also likely to include strategic dialogue. Further information will be provided in due course. The contract will be awarded without further advertisement of this opportunity and there will be no further opportunity to express interest. The indicative affordability threshold is Â£7,400,000 per annum and the Contract will be for a duration of 3 years. The QQ documentation should be completed and submitted by 5pm on 20th December 2017.

column47: Architectural led team for the production of a Delivery Plan for the Sutton Town Centre Regeneration
column48:
The Council is seeking to commission a multi-disciplinary team to build upon the conclusions of the Town Centre Masterplan and prior transport/highways  studies, to create a Delivery Plan for the comprehensive regeneration of Sutton Town Centre. The delivery plan will set a clear strategy for regeneration which will find solution to our regeneration challenges and deliver our ambitions.  
The Delivery Plan will underpin our strategy for townscape, public realm and gyratory transformation. It will inform the production of SPDs which will promote our desire to comprehensively develop the town centre, avoid piecemeal development and incorporate polycentric city principles.
The Delivery Plan will guide our land assembly strategy, disposal of assets and developer activity in the town centre.
The successful bidder will be a renowned architectural practice who will lead a multidisciplinary team to provide a clear vision and strategy for regeneration. We anticipate that the team will include urban design, transport planning, cost consultant, development consultancy and specialist retail regeneration advisor. 
The team will display  significant experience in delivering ambitious and innovative placemaking regeneration schemes. You will be well versed in engaging public sector stakeholders and have the confidence to challenge ingrained positions to deliver regeneration.

column47: Expressions of Interest sought for delivery of new National Careers Service in NW
column48:
ESFA have initiated the process of procuring the new National Careers Service (NCS) across England. The National Careers Service provides information, advice and guidance to help people make decisions on learning, training and work. The service offers confidential and impartial advice and is delivered by qualified careers advisers. The service delivered through the new area based contracts will primarily be 'face to face' with a focus on nationally defined priority groups.

Career Connect (formerly Greater Merseyside Connexions Partnership - GMCP) is a Matrix accredited Charity delivering Information, Advice and Guidance (IAG) services and intensive support that enables young people and adults across the North West achieve their potential. We have delivered NCS since 1997, when it was known as Next Step. We have been prime contract holders for the NW NCS and hold Prime contracts for services including ESFA/ESF NEET and NOMS CFO3 programmes. We hold the Merlin Standard for supply chain management.

We are seeking Expressions of Interest from providers who would like to form part of our supply chain covering the NW area based contract for Liverpool City Region, Greater Manchester, Cheshire, Warrington and Lancashire. To find out more, including instructions on how to express your interest please go to http://www.careerconnect.org.uk/partnerships. The DEADLINE for submission is 6pm 30 November 2017.

primary and secondary schools, to individuals, groups, families, and professional drivers, for the next 3 years.
Cycle training forms a key part of the Council's behavior change programme, with the intention of getting more
people cycling, more often and even more safely. This objective is one of the main components of the Cycling
Strategy (2014), The Contract Period is initially for a period of 36 months although the Council reserves the right to extend the Contract on the same terms for a further period or periods of up to 12 months + 12 months making a total possible Contract Period of 60 months. Potential Providers are to note that TUPE will apply to this contract.

The registered user will receive a notification email to alert them once this has been done.
As a user of the e-Tendering Suite you will have access to proactis e-portal email messaging service

Please note it is your responsibility to access these emails on a regular basis to ensure you have sight of all

column47: 9710 - Citizen magazine distribution services - AWARD
column48:
Citizen magazine is an invaluable publication for Norwich residents to turn to and rely on for factual, council information. 
      
      The magazine is distributed at four set times each year which allows the council to keep residents up to date with important council news - be that changes to the waste and recycling service, the outcome of local elections, how they can give the council their views on important consultations which will affect them and information about the essential services the council provides.
      
      Each issue of Citizen has a print run of about 66,700 copies.
      
      The council is looking for a supplier to manage the distribution of the magazine to Norwich households (residential only) via unaddressed Door to Door mail and addressed direct mail service for its spring 2018 issue onwards. 
      
      The contract for this service is planned to start early December 2017 and run for two years with an option to extend for an additional two years (on a one-year at-a-time basis).
      
      The first issue due for distribution under this contract will be in the first complete week of March 2018 (exact date to be provided post tender).

column47: Inductively Coupled Plasma Mass Spectrometer
column48:
The Health & Safety Laboratory (HSL) of the Health & Safety Executive (HSE) is inviting tenders for the supply of an Inductively Coupled Plasma Mass Spectrometer (ICPMS). 
      
      HSL undertakes routine low-level elemental analysis in biological fluids on behalf of HSE and also for a number of HSL's external customers.   This analysis takes the form of testing of human exposure to contamination within the metals industry (e.g. cadmium and lead) and many other industries with exposures to a wide range of elements (welding, recycling, surface engineering etc). In order to deliver on the growing number of biological analysis undertaken and on new planned projects it is necessary to replace an older ICPMS instrument with a newer, more reliable and sensitive instrument

Additional information: 1. In order to gain access to the documentation and to respond to this opportunity you will be required to register, free of charge, on to HSE's e-Procurement portal by accessing the following link: https://in-tendhost.co.uk/hse/aspx/Home 

2. The deadline for all questions is noon on 29/11/17.  Responses wil be provided by close of play 13/12/17.  The deadline for receipt of tenders is 2pm on 29/12/17.



Delivery Notes

Delivery is to HSE's Health & Safety Laboratory in Buxton, SK17 9JN

column47: GB-London: Asbestos Surveys, Removals and Management
column48:
Under the Control of Asbestos Regulations 2012 (Reg. 4) Places of Worship and historic buildings have a duty to manage the asbestos contained within them. This tender invites submissions from organisations or sole traders who are qualified to deliver a range of Asbestos Management Services (including  Asbestos Surveys and remedial works from licensed and non-licensed contractors), to listed and unlisted Places of Worship and Historic Buildings ( including associated domestic and non-domestic buildings) across England and Wales,  as commissioned by Registered Users ( Users) through  the MaintenanceBooker service, a national procurement portal ran by 2buy2 and the National Churches Trust.
      
      LOT 1.Asbestos  Management & Refurbishment /Demolition  Surveys - the supplier shall be suitably qualified and accredited to undertake Asbestos Management, Re-inspection,  Refurbishment and Demolition  Surveys in accordance with HSG 264 Asbestos : The Survey Guide and all work to be  undertaken in accordance with all processes and procedures according to legislation and approved codes of practice.
      
      LOT 2.Asbestos Remediation & Removal Works 
      a.the supplier shall be fully licensed to undertake the remediation or removal of all levels  of Asbestos Containing Materials (ACM's) to comply with HSG 247 Asbestos : The Licensed Contractor's Guide and all work to be undertaken in accordance with all processes and procedures according to legislation and approved codes of practice
      b.The supplier is not licensed but is suitably qualified to carry out non-licensed work involving asbestos in compliance with Asbestos Essentials -  a task manual for building, maintenance and allied trades of non-licensed asbestos works as per Asbestos essentials task manual: Task guidance sheets for the building maintenance and allied trades HSG210.
      
      LOT 3.Asbestos Management Services- the supplier must be suitably qualified  and accredited to undertake the full range of  Asbestos surveys  (as LOT 1) for Users and also licensed to undertake the remediation or removal of all levels of ACM's  or suitably licensed to act as a consultant to manage and supervise the remediation or removal of all levels of ACM's.  All work to be undertaken in accordance with all processes and procedures according to legislation and approved codes of practice.

Additional information: The contracting authority considers that this contract may be suitable for economic operators that are small or medium enterprises (SMEs). However, any selection of tenderers will be based solely on the criteria set out for the procurement.

column47: Invitation to Tender for the provision of a framework of contractors for building works and associated electrical works, to provide responsive maintenance services to the housing repairs section, commercial properties and Pleasley Vale Mills Business Park
column48:
Bolsover District Council aims to establish a framework of contractors for building works and associated electrical works, to provide responsive maintenance services to the housing repairs section, commercial properties and Pleasley Vale Mills Business Park.  The Council is working as part of a Strategic Alliance with North East Derbyshire District Council and as such these frameworks will be available for use by NEDDC with no obligation on them to do so. Neither Council guarantees volumes of work offered through the frameworks.  Each of the frameworks will be let as a two year framework with the option of two extensions of up to twelve months each.
      
      How to Express Interest in this Tender: 
      
      1. Register your company on the eSourcing portal (this is only required once) - Browse to the eSourcing Portal: https://in-tendhost.co.uk/noecpc and click the link to register - Enter your correct business and user details - Note: your username will be the email address you have entered - you will also then shortly receive an email confirmation. 
      2. Once registered access the site and from the Home page hover over 'Tenders' on the tool bar  and select 'current tenders' from the drop down options
      3. Express Interest in the tender you are interested in - Select `Express Interest` within the Tender Details ( located at the bottom of the synopsis).  On doing so, you will instantly have access to the Tender Management area for that tender.  Any available documentation will be available via the various relevant tabs.  You can access this area at any point by logging in, navigating to `My Tenders` and selecting `View Details`.
      4. Responding to the tender - There will be a tab allocated to any tender stage (e.g. SQ and/or ITT).  Under the `My Tender Return` area, you will be required to complete any mandatory questionnaires and upload any requested documentation. column47: Tender for Positive Behavioural Support Service
column48:
The Positive Behavioural Support service will work with identified young people, their parents / carers and other professionals that deliver support to the young person. The PBS service will identify a suitable individual Behaviour Support plan for each young person. The PBS service will deliver intensive support to the parents / carers and other professionals to implement the behaviour support model required for that young person, working in the variety of settings that the young person is in to ensure a consistent approach to behaviour management across those settings and the relevant family members / professionals. 

The key aims of this proposed Positive Behavioural Support Service (PBS) are as follows:
â¢	To improve outcomes for children within the Bradford District who have learning disabilities and behaviours that challenge
â¢	To improve the wellbeing of the parents / carers and families of children who have learning disabilities and behaviours that challenge
â¢	To make savings on the amount that the Council is currently paying for full time residential care placements
It is expected that this service will be funded through a Social Investment model with payment being made for outcomes successfully achieved.

1786/341/MY/NAMRC/17        Welding Manipulator 

The University of Sheffield wishes to invite tenders for a Welding Manipulator on behalf of the Advanced Manufacturing Research Centre, Nuclear AMRC Group at Catcliffe, South Yorkshire.

Scope of Requirement

Nuclear AMRC require manipulation equipment to facilitate large scale diode laser cladding work. At current the Nuclear AMRC do not have the capability to manipulate large geometry components typical of small modular reactors (SMRs). By targeting this capability, potential work within the SMR market will be achievable and large assembly demonstrators can be manufactured.

column47: Arboricultural Services - Provision of Tree Surveys, Inspections, Maintenance
column48:
Place Partnership Ltd. invite suitable, qualified and experienced Arboricultural Contractors to carry i) Tree Surveys & Inspections and ii) Tree Maintenance for its constituent partners in the counties of Herefordshire, Warwickshire, Worcestershire and Shropshire. 
      
      The contract will run for an initial term of 2 years and will be reviewed following a period of 18 months with the possibility of a 1 year extension period thereafter.
      
      Anticipated start date: 01st February 2018
      
      The successful supplier will need to demonstrate a commercially competitive model that will demonstrate a commercial, environmental and innovative approach that would be of benefit to the Partnering Authorities whilst maintaining the highest levels of safety.
      
      The purpose of the contract is to enhance the environment and ensure that our Partner's trees are well managed, in particular to: 
      
      o trees are maintained in a healthy vigorous condition through a pro-active inspection and maintenance regime
      
      o minimise the risk to persons and property
      
      o take the opportunity to increase the number of trees where appropriate on our partners estate.
      
      o increase bio-diversity and minimise the adverse effects of maintenance activities on the environment
      
      For certain of our sites operatives will be required to have Non Police Personnel Vetting Level 1 (NPPV 1) and a Disclosure Barring Service certificate (DBS)
       
      Whilst the specification is divided into two sections i) Surveys/Inspections ii) Maintenance  we are seeking to appoint a sole contractor for both lots however we reserve the right to appoint a contractor for each lot.
      
      It is on this basis that we invite suitable contractors to provide a full turn-key contract compliant quotation, to deliver this contract within set time scales.
      
      All tender documents must be uploaded to the portal by the due date as late returns will not be accepted.
      
      Tenders and supporting documents shall be in English and any contract subsequently entered in to shall be subject to English Law.
      
      Please note that the Supplier is responsible for obtaining all information necessary for the preparation of the tender submission. All cost, expenses and liabilities incurred by the Supplier in connection with the preparation of their submission, the Form of Tender and Pricing Schedule shall be borne by the Supplier.
      
      Place Partnership Ltd. reserve the right not to award a contract in full or in part.

Additional information: 
To register your interest and to download all of the  tender documents please visit the Place Partnership e-procurement portal at:

column47: Cheshire Archives and Local Studies
column48:
Cheshire Archives and Local Studies identifies, collects and cares for archives and publications that are the evidence of Cheshire's communities lives past and present.  We deliver access for all of our collections for information, learning and enjoyment to make sure archives survive so that future generations will be able to do the same.

Cheshire Archives and Local Studies is headquartered at the Cheshire Record Office in Chester, where it has been based since 1985. The building is no longer fit-for-purpose as storage conditions and space do not meet current standards and accommodation for staff, volunteers and public falls below current expectations. Increasingly its suitability is being questioned on health and safety grounds.
Elected members in both authorities have approved the development of a delivery model for the service which sees two new History Centres being developed as bases for the service. One will be a 'headquarters' building in Chester and the second facility will be in Crewe. Sites were allocated to the project in September 2017 and both facilities will be new build. Funding has been secured to develop a First Round Heritage Lottery Fund grant application around this delivery model. It is anticipated that a HLF grant application will be in the region of Â£4 million and to this end a First Round submission is expected be submitted in early 2018. The Councils are therefore seeking a range of consultancy services to support the preparation of this application, namely:
-	Activity Planning
-	Interpretation and Exhibition
-	Business Planning
-	External bid writing support

column47: 16 023 Cheshire Councils ERP Project
column48:
Cheshire East Borough Council and Cheshire West and Chester Council (The Authorities) have undertaken a Competitive Dialogue procedure to procure a framework agreement for the design, build and implementation of an integrated enterprise resource planning (ERP) solution and the provision of ongoing support and maintenance. The core services impacted are Finance, Procurement, Human Resources and Payroll. The Framework Agreement will commence on 22.9.2017 for a period of 4 years. Individual call off contracts awarded under the Framework Agreement is for an initial term of 7 years with the option to extend for a further period(s) up to a maximum extension of 5 years. Both Authorities entered into a call off contract under the Framework on the same day as the award. In addition to the Authorities, Warrington Borough Council, Wirral Metropolitan Borough Council, Trafford Metropolitan Borough Council and Stockport Metropolitan Borough Council are entitled, but not obliged, to call off services. The 4 Year Framework Agreement is awarded to a single supplier which was entered into by Cheshire East Council. The call-off contracts under the Framework Agreement are for an initial term of 7 years with the option to extend for 1 or more periods of up to 5 years. The value of the Framework Agreement is estimated to be approximately 42-50 000 000 GBP but will be dependent on the Authorities and Related Councils' decision whether to use the Framework Agreement. Owing to the size/nature of the services and help to ensure the best service continuity, the Authorities have decided not to subdivide the contract services into Lots. The scope includes the implementation of modules offering improved functionality and solution refreshes during the term.

No guarantee or warranty has been given as to the nature or volume of the Services or the number of call offs under the Framework Agreement. The values given in this notice are only estimations and are for the initial 7 year contract period and also take into account the extension option of up to a further 60 months.

The Authority gives no guarantee or warranty or makes any representation as to the accuracy of any indicative volumes or as to the value of the work during the contract period.

column47: Supply and installation of controlled environment systems within plant growth facilities
column48:
The purpose is to simulate various climate regimes so that the response of different potted trees can be investigated, modelled and predicted under climate change. The basic infrastructure and temperature control units have already been installed and this contract will extend the equipment such that a wider range of environmental factors can be investigated. 

This involves the supply and installation of benching, lighting, roof shade screens, irrigation system, and CO2 and relative humidity control into an existing controlled environment growth house (comprising four growing compartments and one compartment with controller units). It includes sensors, control units and extension of the computer software to monitor, control and record the environmental conditions in each growing compartment.

Benching: static benches, each 3650mm wide x 760mm long with 10swg galvanised weld mesh tops.

Supplementary lighting: LED Toplights plus connection to existing computer control system; additional software  added to the existing control system to control of lights based on timeclock or external radiation sum; 'Unistrut' supporting frame or equivalent
Roof screens: cloth, support wires, drive mechanisms, slipping elements, cloth guides, sealing blocks
Manual Side and Gable Screens: screens and supporting framework 
Irrigation: mist propagation systems including mist controller units, wet leaf sensors, and mist bench hoops
Modification to Existing Water Pipes to install Dosatrons:
Relative humidity control: humidifiers and hygrostats
CO2 Control: pipes, valves, sensors, regulators, connections to computer controls
Upgrade to computer monitoring
Please express your interest in this tender to Helen McKay at the Northern Research Station by email by the 29th of September 2017 to allow us to notify you of any questions and answers we may receive.

Brief Description of Requirement

National Oceanography Centre (NOC) is seeking interest from qualified engineering firms to undertake the combined roles of Principle Contractor and Designer for the professional services associated with the above Design & Build project. This contract will be awarded subject to NEC3 Engineering and Construction Contract (ECC) Terms and Conditions.  

The Joseph Proudman building is located at 6 Brownlow Street, Liverpool L3 5DA.

The motorised window opening chain box system was installed as part of the original build on floors two, three and four and is circa 12 years old. The control system, Window Master, for the motorised windows is closed protocol and independent of the main Building Management System, Siemens Desigo Insight.
The window control protocol is informed by wall mounted room sensors and the primary control parameters are internal temperature and CO2 levels. In addition the system includes a roof mounted weather station which allows for heavy rain/high wind control functions.  It has been observed that the under control system often 'fights' the heating system in the summer resulting in overheating of the building and increased heat consumption.
